\begin_layout Standard
But how do we know which frequencies and intensities to use in approximation?
 In principle, the answer is simple.
 Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:best-approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides the guidance.
 Orthogonal projection of the function gives the right intensities.
 All we need are an appropriate inner product space and a basis for some
 subspace.
 Except in extreme cases, pressure waves, and therefore sound waves, vary
 continuously, so it makes sense to consider the vector space of continuous
 functions over some interval.
 In particular, we will consider subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left([0,L]\right)$
\end_inset

, the set of all functions which are continuous on the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much like the inner products of exercises 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:inner-product-4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exc:inner-product-5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Inner-Product-Spaces"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,g\rangle=\int_{0}^{L}f(x)g(x)\,dx$
\end_inset

 defines an inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left([0,L]\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Can you justify it? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:inner-product-on-V0L"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left([0,L]\right)$
\end_inset

 are continuous functions, so a basis for any subspace will have to be a
 collection of functions which are continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

.
 As suggested by their use earlier, collections of trigonometric functions
 provide convenient bases.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \cos\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right),\cos\left(\frac{n\pi}{L}t\right)\right\rangle =0\label{eq:cosines-are-orthogonal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right),\sin\left(\frac{n\pi}{L}t\right)\right\rangle =0\label{eq:sines-are-orthogonal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq n$
\end_inset

.
 That is, for any distinct positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{n\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal, as are 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\frac{n\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Inner products (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cosines-are-orthogonal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sines-are-orthogonal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be verified with the help of two trigonometric identities.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\alpha\pm\beta)=\cos\alpha\cos\beta\mp\sin\alpha\sin\beta$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}\left[\cos(\alpha-\beta)+\cos(\alpha+\beta)\right]=\cos\alpha\cos\beta\label{eq:cosine-product}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}\left[\cos(\alpha-\beta)-\cos(\alpha+\beta)\right]=\sin\alpha\sin\beta.\label{eq:sine-product}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Can you use (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sine-product"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to show (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sines-are-orthogonal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:sine-functions-are-orthogonal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, when 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and provides another function orthogonal to all 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m>0$
\end_inset

.
 And now we have our candidates for a vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left([0,L]\right)$
\end_inset

, and basis elements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m>0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the function of interest takes the value zero at both endpoints of
 the interval, as is the case for the sound waves we have looked at, it
 makes best sense to use sine functions for a basis.
 Every sine function of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\frac{m\pi}{L}t\right)$
\end_inset

 takes the value zero at both 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=L$
\end_inset

 so the approximation is exact at the endpoints no matter how many basis
 elements are used.
 If the function were nonzero at either endpoint, it would make more sense
 to use cosine functions for a basis as this allows approximation of the
 nonzero endpoint(s).
