\begin_layout Standard
Given a continuous function, we choose a set of sine functions or a set
 of cosine functions as basis for a subspace and we project onto the subspace
 to find the best approximation.
 For example, consider approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x(x-1)(x-2)$
\end_inset

 over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2]$
\end_inset

.
 How closely can we approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by vectors in the spans of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{1}=\left\{ 1,\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right),\cos\left(\pi t\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 (from the family of cosine functions with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0,1,2$
\end_inset

)?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Description
Answer: The best approximation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\text{proj}_{\text{span}\{\mathcal{B}_{1}\}}f$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\langle f,1\rangle}{\langle1,1\rangle}1+\frac{\left\langle f,\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right)\right\rangle }{\left\langle \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right),\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right)\right\rangle }\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right)+\frac{\left\langle f,\cos\left(\pi t\right)\right\rangle }{\left\langle \cos\left(\pi t\right),\cos\left(\pi t\right)\right\rangle }\cos\left(\pi t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Using a computer algebra system to help with the integration,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=-16\frac{\pi^{2}-12}{\pi^{4}}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Due to symmetry, the first and third terms are zero.
 The distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Inner-Product-Spaces"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(f,\mathbf{v})=\left\Vert f-\mathbf{v}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\left\langle f-\mathbf{v},f-\mathbf{v}\right\rangle }\approx0.0299.
\]

\end_inset

The graphs of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 are shown below with the area between the two shaded over the interval
 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2]$
\end_inset

.
 Since the distance between 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 involves integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f-\mathbf{v}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, the shaded area does not represent the distance between the vectors exactly,
